  "title": "Verbs Group A (-o)",
  "reading_greek": "THE PATTERN (Stem is Stressed)\n- Κάνω (I do)\n- Κάνεις (You do)\n- Κάνει (He/She does)\n- Κάνουμε (We do)\n- Κάνετε (You do)\n- Κάνουν (They do)\n\nCOMMON VERBS\n- Μένω (I live/stay)\n- Περιμένω (I wait)\n- Διαβάζω -> Διαβάζουμε (I read -> We read)\n- Γράφω -> Γράφει (I write -> He writes)\n- Πίνω (I drink)\n- Μαθαίνω (I learn)\n- Δουλεύω -> Δουλεύω (I work - I work)",
  "reading_english": "GRAMMAR: GROUP A VERBS [(See Page 54)](/assets/grammar.pdf#page=54)\n\n1. IDENTIFY IT: The accent is on the STEM, not the ending. \n   - KA-no, not ka-NO.\n\n2. ENDINGS:\n   - o, eis, ei\n   - oume, ete, oun\n\n3. STRESS: The stress usually stays on the same syllable. \n   - KA-no, KA-neis, KA-noume.",
  "audio_script": "Group A Verbs. The biggest family of verbs. \n\nThey are easy to spot. The stress is on the root. 'KA-no', 'ME-no', 'PI-no'.\n\nConjugation check:\n- I: -o\n- You: -eis\n- He/She: -ei\n\n- We: -oume\n- You (pl): -ete\n- They: -oun\n\n'Meno' (I live). 'Meneis' (You live). 'Menei' (He lives). \n'Menoume' (We live). 'Menete' (You live). 'Menoun' (They live).\n\nLearn this pattern, and you know 80% of Greek verbs.",
